    43: {
      id: 43,
      name: 'The Natural Duties of a Kṣatriya',
      devanagari: 'शौर्यं तेजो धृतिर्दाक्ष्यं युद्धे चाप्यपलायनम् ।\nदानमीश्वरभावश्च क्षात्रं कर्म स्वभावजम् ॥',
      transliteration: 'śauryaṁ tejo dhṛtir dākṣyaṁ yuddhe cāpy apalāyanam\ndānam īśvara-bhāvaś ca kṣātraṁ karma svabhāva-jam',
      translation: 'Heroism, vitality, resolve, skill, not fleeing in battle, generosity, and capacity for governance — these are the natural duties of a Kṣatriya.',
      words: [
        { word: 'śauryam tejaḥ dhṛtiḥ dākṣyam', meaning: 'heroism, vitality, resolve, skill / the four active qualities of the warrior-protector' },
        { word: 'yuddhe ca api apalāyanam', meaning: 'and also not fleeing in battle / and the quality of standing firm under pressure' },
        { word: 'dānam īśvara-bhāvaḥ ca', meaning: 'and generosity and capacity for governance / giving and the disposition of a leader' },
        { word: 'kṣātram karma svabhāva-jam', meaning: 'the natural duty of a Kṣatriya / the action born of the warrior-protector nature' }
      ],
      commentary: `The Kṣatriya function is built around śaurya (heroism — the willingness to act courageously in the face of genuine threat), tejas (vitality, inner fire — the quality of presence and energy that commands respect), dhṛti (resolve — the steadiness to maintain course under pressure), and dākṣya (skill, adeptness — the practical capacity to execute well in demanding conditions).\n\nApalāyanam — not fleeing — is the specific Kṣatriya virtue that defines the entire Gita's opening context. Arjuna's paralysis on the battlefield was a failure of this quality. The Kṣatriya function requires facing difficulty directly, not avoiding it. This is the quality that the teaching has been restoring throughout the eighteen chapters.\n\nDāna (generosity) and īśvara-bhāva (the disposition of a leader — the capacity to govern, protect, and take responsibility for others) complete the portrait. The Kṣatriya type is not simply a fighter. They are a protector who is generous with their strength and carries the disposition of genuine leadership — not autocracy, but the willingness to bear responsibility for the welfare of others. In contemporary terms, these qualities describe anyone in a position of genuine leadership, regardless of military context.`
    },

