      commentary: `Sañjaya's closing words are not a report — they are a testimony of joy. Saṁsmṛtya saṁsmṛtya: remembering again and again. The repetition is not grammatical accident; it mirrors the lived experience Sañjaya is describing. He keeps going back to the memory of this dialogue, and each time he does, hṛṣyāmi — he rejoices. Muhur muhuḥ: again and again, continuously.\n\nThis is the Gita's own description of what genuine reception produces: not just understanding but joy. The one who has truly heard the Gita does not simply have a collection of philosophical positions. They have a living resource — a conversation they can return to again and again and find it always yields something new, always produces the same delight in the heart that genuine contact with the sacred produces.\n\nKeśava: the name of Kṛṣṇa as the one with beautiful hair, but also understood as the destroyer of the demon Keśī and as the master of the senses. Puṇyam: holy, auspicious, merit-producing — the word used for acts and objects that carry a sacred quality beyond their visible nature. The dialogue between Keśava and Arjuna is described as holy — not just valuable or wise but sacred, carrying a quality that nourishes the soul.`
