      commentary: `The Gita does not end with Arjuna's words. It ends with Sañjaya's — the narrator who has been watching the entire dialogue from a distance. These are his final words, and they close not just the Gita but the arc of the entire Mahābhārata in miniature.\n\nYatra yogeśvaraḥ Kṛṣṇo yatra pārtho dhanur-dharaḥ — wherever the Lord of Yoga is, and wherever the skilled actor takes up their instrument. This is not just a statement about two historical figures on a battlefield. It is a description of a relationship — between the divine intelligence and the human being who has aligned with it.\n\nThe Lord of Yoga represents the source: the infinite, the unchanging, the one who holds all things. The bearer of the bow represents the embodied person who has done the inner work, recovered their clarity, and is now ready to act with full skill. When these two are together — when action arises from genuine alignment with something deeper than ego — the results are śrī, vijaya, bhūti, nīti: prosperity, victory, flourishing, and unwavering righteousness.\n\nDhruvā — unwavering. Fixed. Certain. Not dependent on circumstances. Sañjaya ends with matir mama: this is my conviction. Having watched the entire conversation, having witnessed the transformation of Arjuna from paralysis to readiness, he says: I am certain of this. When the right force is behind you — not force you manufactured, but force you aligned with — victory is not a hope. It is a certainty. That is the final word of the Gita.`,
